segments.text: And we're in 209 Francis Hall, getting ready to chat with Les Reed.
Les, check yours.
I think mine's probably at a good level.
Les, for the sake of the person who may listen to this tape or read the transcription many years from now,
Let's begin by asking you to summarize your biography before you came here.
Where did you grow up?
Where did you study?
What were you doing before you came to A&M?
Well, okay, Haskell, I was a depression baby.
I was born just in May of 29, just four or five months before the October crash.
And so that influenced the early childhood.
However,
I was born in Niagara Falls, New York, of parents who were both native born and naturalized.
My mother was a naturalized Canadian.
And consequently, my people were pretty heavily Scotch-Canadian.
Being in Niagara Falls, my early childhood was influenced by tourism and parks and overlooks and all the trappings that go with that.
and a father that was heavily oriented toward the outdoors and sports.

So my youth was spent from cub scouting and boy scouting and adventure scouting and Canadian family vacations every year to enjoy that sort of thing, which after my dad was moved by the DuPont Company to manage a

chemical plant in suburban downriver detroit michigan we moved there and i was about twelve junior high school age and completed high schooling uh... there in michigan hated the industrial side of life wanted to be an outdoorsman escaped from home wanted to go as far away as i could and still pay in-state tuition so i ended up at the forestry school in the upper peninsula michigan michigan

technological colleges it was called at that Michigan College of Mines had been its original name famous mining school and very briefly from Michigan Tech got out just during the start of the Korean War went into the Army into the Signal Corps enlisted actually for two years which was possible at that time which I was told was a better deal than being conscripted and going in as a draftee
So I enlisted for two years, never got to Korea, ended up teaching in the Department of Electricity at the US Military Academy at West Point.
Don't know how that happened.
Knew very little about electricity when I went in, hardly enough to change a light bulb.
Would have been one of that good Aggie team that changes light bulbs.
But in any event, completed my service there.
Came out and went right back to college with a newly born baby.

girl as a way to get back into the job market and majored there in the college of agriculture and municipal park administration worked as city forester and deputy park commissioner in topeka kansas for a couple years after graduation loved it but decided there was a lot more i wanted to know and
and ended up being invited to come back and teach at Michigan State as long as I would work on a doctorate.
Well, I agreed to that, went back there I think in 57, and ended up taking two doctorates, partly.
The first I was allowed to take as a full-time faculty member a course a semester.
So I took about four years in the wildlife

department which was a related agriculture field until i had a slight rupture with the current department head in wildlife and i remember being dumb as dirt i told him he was only interested in the minutia of bass and bunnies and couldn't see the larger aspects of of urban recreation needs got thrown out of there and transferred what i could to the university of michigan and ended up
with a PhD in National Conservation Policy.
After, what's between Michigan and A&M, in terms of your experience?
Well, nothing, because I was still, by a very hard-nosed but lovable Dean of Agriculture, allowed to maintain a quarter-time appointment at Michigan State, and the bulk of my

doctorate time was funded by the outdoor recreation resources review commission in Washington DC that was making a nationwide study and in fact that financed my PhD I traveled the highway back and forth the 60 some miles between Michigan State and the University of Michigan with my textbooks on the steering wheel and another job part-time in in my hometown of Wyandotte working for the city as an urban forester

Terrible way to live a life trying to maintain a family at the same time had two children by then But anyway intended to stay at Michigan State for the rest of my life got the doctorate in 63 In 65 in the spring I was taking a regional field tour in a varsity bus and
with a group of students throughout the Northeast.
We hit the Garment District in New York.
We hit Washington, D.C. We were in the Smokies.
And I was getting repeated phone calls from the campus saying somebody was desperate to talk to me about moving to Texas to a college there.
And I kept putting them off, saying, look, I'm busy.
I've got problems here with students, and we're on a tight schedule.
I'll talk to them when I get back.
I think that was in June or July.
When I got back to the campus, it turned out to be Dr. R.C.
Potts, Dick Potts, who had called me and repeatedly inviting me to come down.
I'd been nominated by some folks as a candidate for a head of a brand new department that President Rutter wanted to establish.
that they're urging, decided to come down, take a look, had very little interest in it.
Came back from that visit, my wife met me at the airport in Ann Arbor, and I said, she said, what do you think?
And I said, it's the smallest little sidewalk nothing town you ever saw in your life.
She said, do you want to do it?
And I said, yeah.
I said, look, it means tearing us up, but we'll only have to stay a year or two if we don't like it.
And the thing that Haskell really persuaded me to come was the personality and the charisma of General Rutter.
Describe that as best you can.
How was that demonstrated?
Well, you have to remember, when I was here that first year, I think there were like 7,700 students here, almost all in the Corps, no women, except a few hardship cases, as they were called, who's...
Family had petitioned the president and said, look, it would be a hardship on us economically for my little girl to go anywhere else.
Would you take her in?
So we had a few grad students, but largely it was a ROTC-uniformed campus.
I was at Michigan State, which was a big 10 power and probably 22,000 students at that time.
I had all my contacts, all my connections, my network.
professionally was in the Lake States.
I knew nothing about southern trees or environment or dirty muddy rivers and so it looked like a big jump.
Dr. Potts met me at the airport.
It was in August.
I had no idea about Texas heat.
I never knew it was hot here because he had a little underdash air conditioning unit

a bolt-on unit in his car he had it turned up all the way i never knew it was hot here i remember going back he took me to hobby airport in houston when my interview visit was over and the the rotating bank temperature on one of the banks down there in houston said 96 and i said i can't believe it and i opened the window and stuck my arm out the window and almost fried
But they had kept me so much in air conditioning during my visit that I didn't know how hot it was.
Actually, the recruitment I did later on in years was always to try and go after northern profs in February for the same reason anybody wanted to get out of the north at that time of year.
So anyway, getting back to General Rutter, because Michigan State was a large campus,
I saw John Hanna, who was the beloved president of that university, and we all adored him, maybe once a year in a reception line for a scant couple of seconds.
I came down here to this school, and among all of the places that Dr. Potts shepherded me to, one was a meeting with President Rutter.
And I went in his top floor office in the systems building,
and had a wonderful conversation with him.
He was pleasant and easy to talk to, told me some of his dreams for the school and what he wanted A&M to become.
And after about an hour, as I remember, as we got up to leave, he walked me to his office door, put an arm around my shoulder, and said, Les, I really need you to come here and help me do this thing.
And I melted.
That's how Jesus' disciples must have felt.
I'll follow you anywhere.
I'll do anything to be with you.
And that's what I told my wife, is that I really want to do this.
Did he seem genuinely concerned about recreation and parks?
He didn't know what he was talking about.
Actually, he told me about his background as land commissioner and a drug store owner in Brady and things of that kind and not much about his Army experience.
I found out that later what a hero he was.
But his idea was that recreation was something that his neighbors and landowners could profit from and benefit from

as an additional use of their land during hard times when you know cow prices and sheep were down through hunting privileges and so he kind of saw outdoor recreation quote unquote as farm hunting more like a fish and wildlife ranger following that same thread
Did you know then or do you know now who originated the idea of creating such a program?
Yeah.
Yeah, Dr. Chuck Leinweber, Charles Leinweber of Enrange Science.
As a matter of fact, he had been for a couple of years under Dean Patterson, Dean of Agriculture, been carrying a few students that wanted to specialize in outdoor resource management.
And that was the unusual thing about what Rudder was proposing to me, which was that Dean Patterson had set up a multi-department committee to recommend to him how to deal with this thing.
And rather than build it as an adjunct out of range science, decided to make it a separate department along with range
in wildlife and forestry, because that's the typical pattern in land grant schools around the country.

And so Lineweber was kind of the nursemaid to that situation, and they went out and looked at candidates and somehow or other, I guess I'd been somewhat visible through this National ARC research study and had published in that, they decided to take a look at me.

Things all go together, I think, according to God's will, because the time I'd spend at the military academy, watching the cadets marching on the plane and all that kind of stuff, it seemed like coming home to come to A&M in a way.
And so the idea for Milan Weber, through the dean, through Vice President Wayne Hall and Rudder,
As far as you were aware, everybody had signed on.
Creation of this brand new department.
And what was it called at organization time?
Recreation and Parks.
Recreation and Parks.
But it included what we today might call also tourism?
No.
Did not?
No.
It was largely conceived as an adjunct to a game warden
kind of program.
That's originally what I think General Rudder was looking at, specializing in recreation, but in a very farm outdoor hunting kind of arrangement.
And what did they offer you in terms of resources to build this department, to create it?
Nobody offered me anything except

for President Rutter and as we left he said if you come and if you'll give me the top national program in the country you'll have a blank check as long as I'm here and you know the interesting thing Haskell is that being young and inexperienced I bought that but it could have been all fluff it could have been very insincere I could have come and been a single prof working and frustrated the rest of my life with none of that
And there wouldn't be anything you could do about it.
But he was absolutely 100% committed to this thing.
Right.
When you got at some point in writing an offer of employment, did that offer include any promises about the department's creation in terms of resources and so forth?
They said no.
Dean Patterson, through Dick Potts, who was the chief negotiator with me, said that we will do our best to find you space.
We're very tight on space.
That hasn't changed much, has it, over the years?
And the salary they offered me was $11,000 a year on a 12-month basis, which was about...
I think I was at $8,600 a year or something like that in 1965 at Michigan State at that time.
So it was a very, very healthy increase.
Plus we figured the cost of living might be somewhat less here.
It was a wrench leaving all our family and relatives.
But we thought for a few years it wouldn't be such a bad deal.
Incidentally, my reporting time was to be December of 65.
Before that time came, I got a letter from the Ag Dean's office and found that my starting salary had increased, without me being there, from $11,000 to $11,800.
Incredible.
Because some of those first few years were very good as President Rutter tried to raise the salaries.
commensurate with other places and in order to attract good faculty.
He was on a real push to get out of state faculty.
In fact, I have to tell you a little anecdote.
I sent a resume when they asked me if I was interested in being considered for this job of department head of a new department.
I sent a resume.
In those days, come on now,

five we had no computers available everything was done on stencils and typewriter and i sent a copy of my resume in my in my military experience i listed my highest rank because i had always been in a school company been in the signal corps been in this been in that school advanced microwave theory and finally teaching at west point i listed corporal
which was my highest rank, Corporal, U.S. Army Signal Corps, U.S. Military Academy, West Point.
And I realized years later, because of the copying techniques that we used, it looked like what?
Colonel.
Colonel, C-O-L, not C-P-L. And I told Dorothy, that's probably the only reason I got the position was, you know, most of the senior people on this campus were retired military.
And so Colonel from West Point, that can't be too bad.
He'll fit right in.
All right.
Surely, as you move down here, there must be one or two good stories about the experiences of moving from Michigan to Texas with a young family and all your belongings.
Well, we had everything other than having a Mayflower van that was following us.
But we left there the day after Christmas.
in a howling snowstorm and went to pay one last visit to my Niagara Falls relatives from Detroit.
So we crossed into Canada.
In Biggie Munn's car, I had bought his big Dodge 880 station wagon with the thought of going to Texas.
Just happened he had turned it in and I bought it.
So we had it loaded to the gills, and the Ontario Provincial Police stopped me and said, young man, do you realize that you're going 60 miles an hour, and it's icy and slippery?
And I just had transfer plates on it, so they didn't know where I was from.
So he let me go when I assured him that I knew how to drive on ice and snow.
But that was the weather we left.

two days later, we were driving down through Elvis Presley's hometown, Tupelo, Mississippi, shedding all of our parkas and heavy coats, and the kids were sweltering in the car, and got into Brian, and the roses were still blooming.
So that was the change in scenery that took place that December.
Where were you first officed?
Where would your first
First office they gave me was in the plant science building on the third floor.
Golly, I can't remember the name, Haskell, of the terrible crotchety old individual in horticulture that was one of the best teachers they ever had.
And you were identified as head of the department.
Head of the department with one office.
One office, and you were the only faculty member.
I was the only faculty member.
In a week, I interviewed a secretary.
They gave me a second office, so I was the secretary.
These were little offices, about 10 by 12.
And so I had one office there.
I was a horticulture prof.
This was a dead-end hall with four small suites, four small offices in the suite.
So I had a department secretary in the next office in the storage room across from her, and I went to a
Southwest Regional Park and Recreation Training Institute at Lake Texoma that was sponsored yearly by Texas Tech's park management curriculum.
And found a young man there who was very unhappy with the PhD program he was in at LSNU.
and persuaded him to come with me to transfer his program.
We had no PhD.
We had no master's.
But we had good connections with Charles Leidenweber, who was still nurse-mating our few graduate students.
And he did.
He came as an instructor, got him appointed.
And I have to tell you a little anecdote about my student body.
Got in there, got unpacking.
that first few days carrying stuff up from the car, and a young fella came in in uniform with his cap in his hand, said, sir, I understand this is going to be Parks and Recreation.
I said, well, Recreation and Parks, yeah.
He said, I want to be in this department.
And he was a transfer,

he became my first student i said if you'll help me shelve some of these books get them out of the boxes and hand them to me i'll talk to you about this as we go he's he was here he was recognized as our outstanding student from years back he has just this year been appointed as the director of state parks in texas after a 25-year career in the national park services

that's called the chief ranger that's the only one in the united states he's chief of all the rangers in all the national parks so he's had a brilliant career and now he's back as director of texas state parks but we shelved those books and he told me last week he still remembers the picture i hung on the wall which was a log cabin in the woods with snow deep all around it and pine trees towering over and he said that's the way i want to live my life
But he was in danger of failing out.
He had about a D average.
And this was a last gasp chance for him to find out something that he liked.
And the rest of that spring semester, Haskell, he was in frequently with some shave-headed friend out of his company saying, sir, here's another boy that needs to be with us in our department.
And by the end of the semester, we had, I think, 17 majors.

Dick Potts had told me now when you get down here we don't want you to teach in the spring semester we I want you to travel learn about the states Michigan had 83 counties Texas has 254 spread all over and he said you need to become familiar with the towns and the resources and the way people think down here well I didn't I was so hungry to get teaching
that between my first instructor and I, we taught four courses that first semester.
When did you go through the red tape routine of getting a degree program authorized by the Coordinating Board and so forth?
Constantly.
Never stopped.
I think that, well, the bachelor's was approved.
Was the Masters approved initially?
Ashworth, his name sticks in my mind.
No, prior to him it was Reed, R-E-E-D, who I always call Sheepstealers, but that's here and there.
Anyway, I still have some of the
proposals that I wrote for the advanced degrees.
One thing they had promised me was that they would do everything possible to get all three degrees.
I said, if we're going to be first class in the country, we have to have a terminal degree.
And without General Rutter, that never, never would have happened.
And the way it happened was the coordinating board, with Lyne Ruber's help, we did prepare and get approval for the masters.

and the bachelors and the coordinating board then in that same action when we requested all three refused the PhD and I was told the reason was you need to develop some graduates and then some masters graduates and then ultimately track faculty and students with enough critical mass to make a PhD
And I argued we'd be 20 years getting to that point.
But what they really wanted me to do was to develop, I would say, like a pyramid, a broad base, a lot of instructors, a lot of assistant professors, fewer associates, and one or two PhDs.
I persuaded, I think I persuaded President Rudder
We had to do it like an ice cream cone.
We had to have a cadre of top, full professors with national reputations if we were going to do this thing.
And he sent me over.
Actually, a couple trips I made to Austin at his behest, he'd call me up and say, I want to go over to Austin.
There's some people I want you to meet, either politicians or legislators.
Can you go?
And I said, of course I can go.
So he said, meet me at the airport.
He had a twin engine plane.
And he wasn't above testing his people, though.
And I remember on one trip coming back in the plane with him, I was sitting in the co-pilot seat, and he said to the pilot, hand less the wheel.
I want him to fly.
Because he knew I was a licensed private pilot.
And I'd be like, buh, buh, buh, buh, buh.
So I flew it about halfway from Austin back, not to land, but it was a faster plane than us.
Comfortable flying, but I think he just wanted to see what I was made out of.
In any event, he sent me to Austin.
I sat down with the commissioner, Reed.
I can't remember his first name.
We will.
Bevington.
Bevington Reed, you're correct.
In any event, we worked on a yellow faculty pad of paper on names for the graduate degrees.
And I wanted resources in it.

wanted recreation in it played around with a lot of different terms there were so many maximum letters you know a limit to the maximum letters could be any way finally decided recreation and aspirin in the middle recreation and resource of development I wanted a strong outdoor environmental flavor in it he said yeah we can do that he said in fact it'll be easier to

because we got a problem with the board he didn't tell me how many but he said we have a significant number of texas tech graduates on the board we will never get you a phd ever that has parks in the title because tech doesn't have one but he said i think we can get recreation and resources development and he did and that's why our uh
Formal title was that, didn't have parks.
Our department continued, and our undergraduate degree was recreation and parks.
Do you have any idea what year that doctoral program was approved?
I can get that for you.
But three or four years into it?
Oh, yeah.
No longer than that.
I think that proposal went in in 69 ASCA.
Those first, we'll say those first four or five years of the 60s,
Did you run into any roadblocks on campus, any impediments at all?
So far, you've indicated that everybody was positive.
Was that true?
To a large degree, yes, but I had a certain amount of turf wars with health and physical education because around the country,

the normal title is health physical education and recreation at this school they didn't have recreation and he wanted it and he was justifiably i guess jealous of something starting that had recreation parks in the title our our main focus was not community recreation which is the focus at most other schools it's therapeutic recreation
and youth recreation and community recreation.
There were a lot of other schools doing that.
We wanted to do something different here that was tied to the resources.
So, yeah, there was every time they would suggest or propose a course that had recreation in the title, Recreation Adventure or something like that,
outdoor recreation, sports, you know, then the curriculum committee at the college level would send it to me, and we'd negotiate with them.
And every time I wanted something, then he would similarly take a hard look at it, and we'd have to compromise.
Trivia, we bounce back to Michigan State for a second.
Did you ever up there encounter a fellow named Woody Verner?
Durwood T. Verner.
Yeah, yeah.
He became a vice president?
And then was president at Oakland when they created that campus, and then went to Nebraska.
The reason I ask is he's class of 1940 here, and he was all everything.
If you look at the yearbook that year, you find Woody Varner in every page.
He was from Cottonwood, Texas, out toward Abilene.
He always laughed.
He was 10%.

of the graduating class of Cottonwood his senior but you didn't know him then I didn't realize I knew him but I didn't realize it was an A&M connection with him because I knew nothing about this school in fact I was living in what we call the faculty bricks up there the Cherry Lane bricks on the Michigan State campus which were two story eight family things and my neighbor across the street was a
teaching in ag economics.
And his wife and mine and his kids and mine and he and I got quite close there over my first year before I moved off to a private house.
Finally I told him that I was being recruited to come and look at a position at Texas A&M.
I said, it's some little place down in Central Texas somewhere.
He said, I was born on that campus.
I said, what are you talking about?
He said, my father was head.
This was James Bonham.
My father was head of ag economics before Ty Tim.
And he had gone to Harvard and so on, and so I had no idea he was from Texas.
He said, I said, what about this?
Should I even go and look at this place?
What kind of a school is it?
And he gave me this background about, what, the poor boys, social misfits, some kind of a thing like that.
And he said, it has the potential to be a great school.
but they're going to have to drag it kicking and screaming into the 20th century.
So I went with that kind of, on that interview, with that kind of a negative almost attitude, and President Rutter just absolutely turned it around.
How did you and your family feel you were received as newcomers in the community?
Very warmly, very warmly.
We rented down in Bryan initially and joined the Presbyterian Church, although both our roots were in a small Baptist church in Michigan.
And Dick Potts nominated me in the spring of 66 to the one Rotary Club in town.
Dean Patterson's associate dean was Harry Kunkel,
and Kunkel was closely connected with Henry Clay, president of First Bank in Bryan, and was on the board of directors of that bank, introduced me to Henry Clay, got me banking there.
I had been a

pretty big fish as city forester and deputy park commissioner in Topeka Kansas which is a state capital and I kind of liked that ambitious inordinately ambitious and and I felt similarly the the warmth and the openness of of Bryan and College Station was easy to feel the separation between the two and the competitiveness of the two instead of

you know I've been involved in bottom municipal administration in Kansas and here were two cities that deserve to be one city and yet there was no way they were going to merge and that was pretty apparent but as far as the people were it was a small tightly knit community we went to get a chair upholstered I remember at Kepchinski's and
when we introduced ourselves, he said, this town is getting so big, I just don't know everybody anymore.
I used to know everybody that came through that door.
So it was that kind of a rather rural community.
As you look back, the fact that you had been at Michigan State, a separate land grant school, was that helpful in your being able to understand A&M a little more quickly?
Oh, absolutely.
Couldn't have done it otherwise because that pattern is so strong through the states.
Michigan State, of course, is proud of the fact that they are the pioneer land grant school.
And here...
John Hutchinson, who was director of Extension, ran Extension as a personal fiefdom.
No, that's not fair.
He ran it as a separate family.
And he took care of his folks, and he demanded a lot of adulation from them, and he got it.
But that, as I went through the years and finally became, Harry Kunkel became dean and I became one of his senior

statesman in terms of longevity, he told us in one staff meeting that he was seriously considering giving up the directorship of the Agricultural Experiment Station, giving that to one of his associates as full director.

and I argued long and hard that he shouldn't do it that it was important as my crusty old Dean Cowden had been in Michigan State to wear all three hats so that ultimately when it came down to a decision point he was able to make that final decision and if if Kunkel gave away that very likely he would rule it someday when they came to a split decision over something and that happened that actually happened
Now, when you arrived, women had just been admitted officially and the corps had just been made optional.
Was that in 66?
I thought it was a little later than that.
Well, it was right about, but we didn't have many women for a number of years because it was primarily for the graduate and professional.
area, not the undergraduate, unless you were a dependent.
When did you, let's go back to, who was your first significant departmental hire?
When did you really hire somebody that began to demonstrate that this program was on the map?
I was very fortunate.
And I'd have to look in our continuity of newsletters to tell you exactly, but I hired an instructor, and then very quickly after, two full professors.
I hired my former department head for Michigan State, who's as near a genius as I'll probably ever meet, but a very great cynic, because he'd seen it all before.
So he was looking for something else.

and then that was Dr. Frank Suggett and so he left Michigan State and came with me and then Claire Gunn who had been on my master's committee and was a landscape architect with strong international tourism leanings was teaching at the University of Hawaii on a short-term basis planning to go back to Michigan State and I lured him to Texas instead
and then brought in Carlton Van Doren out of geography who was came as an associate professor so there was that ice cream cone I wanted to build from the top down.
When you were recruiting those senior people what was the primary point of attraction you could offer them?
A chance to do something that had never been done before.
At Michigan State
Our recreation program and the other resource departments, wildlife fisheries range, were in what was called a conservation institute.
The people were full-time in separate departments, but part of their salary was paid by the conservation institute to do some minor amount of research or work there.
I think the thing that persuaded these senior people to come here to an unknown place and an unknown experience was that I said, I want to turn that model inside out.
I want to own all the salary.
I want to have the institute.
I want to have people with different backgrounds.
But I want to own the whole person.
And so Sugga was a Harvard scholar, outstanding student there.
Dunn was landscape architect.
Van Doren was a geographer.
I'd hired a couple of instructors along the way.
Dave Reed, who was a Texas boy and a graduate of Parks in Texas Tech.
And Dowell, who was a community recreation lad out of Louisiana that had been my first hire.
And the idea was to have people from many different disciplines, but all focusing their energy on some
aspect of outdoor recreation.
Now, did you say to them, we're planning to be first-rate national class?
Absolutely.
Absolutely.
That was the vision that, you know, if they weren't prepared to work toward that end above personal ambition, you know, then don't bother to come.
And particularly in the rudder years, you got support for that goal.
Although you had, let's see, Hall left and Byers became Vice President for Academic Affairs and then Calhoun followed in.
Calhoun was in there.
So that was consistent.
With, at first, on the regional level, you were supposedly comparable to, or compared to Texas Tech.
What other regional
schools, what other schools were there in this region that had a program at all similar?
Moved into a vacuum.
We had about a thousand miles with very little competition.
Texas Tech regarded, well, two things.
I wouldn't have come probably except that

Kunkel as assistant to Dean Patterson really supported me more than I ever should have been supported because you know I wanted everything and he kept he's German and he kept fighting me down and he said well I'm giving you half a loaf you know be satisfied today I said no I want the whole loaf but but he always gave me at least half a loaf before I came

i knew urbanowski through our national associations in recreation and parks and i called elo and he talked to me and he said y'all come on down here we need a little competition you know i'm not afraid of having you down here so he encouraged me to come and start that's the texas tech that's texas tech but he was an a m graduate he claims he was the one that forged the weather vanes on top of the old horse barn
Now, there was no program of this sort at LSU.
No, no.
Nationally, who were your models?
There was kind of a program at Oklahoma State because I found out later Dan Badger, who I'd worked with in the York study, had recommended me here.
Another big supporter that put pressure on some people was Bob Frazier, who was an Aggie,

and director of parks in San Antonio and highly highly respected and he also called me frequently persuading me to come to A&M but you see we had about a thousand miles without anybody there were only about six schools in the country that had any kind of outdoor recreation resource centered parks Colorado State
Syracuse, Michigan State, Cal State, Idaho had a little one.
Cornell?
Yeah, yeah.
But not very significant.
Michigan State was regarded as the top place.
Some people might dispute that, but that was pretty much it.
And the enrollment?
began to do what?
Just skyrocketed.
